Using the built-in CO2 dataset in R, which gives uptake of CO2 in grasses under varying CO2 concentrations, with plants from two locations (Mississippi and Quebec) and two temp treatments; 12 plants, 7 CO2 concentrations for each plant

The default CO2 plant variable is ordered; This recodes it to an unordered factor (see main text for why) GAM for non-linear relationship Spline and basis funtions## Weight of basis determine spline function## Choose values for each coefficient to maximize the likelihood Penaltized likelihood -to decrease wiggliness Lambda is based on AIC G normally REML Effective degree of freedom is always lower than basis complexity Therefore, k should be large enough Too large k has high computational cost Check choice of k with gam.check(), information about residual and p-value etc

plot CO2 uptake vs.CO2 concentration for each plant

model log uptake as a function of two smoothers: thin plate spline of log concentration and RE for individual-plant-specific intercepts

plot the default gratia plot for the CO2 model left: estimated smoother for effect log CO2 concentration on CO2 uptake right: QQ plot of the estimated random effects vs.Gaussian quantiles

Interpreting the summary edfs represent complexity of the smooth; edf = 1 is a straight line, higher edfs mean more wiggly

Interpretation of significance: a significant smooth is one where you cant draw a horizontal line through the 95% CI high edf =/= significance, and vice versa a smooth can be linear and significant, non-linear and non-significant, or one of each

k for log concentration smooth is probably too low

## 
##   95  175  250  350  500  675 1000

but there are only 7 unique values of concentration, so k can be no larger than 7 Setup prediction data (all possible concentration values for all individual plants) make the prediction, add this and a column of standard errors to the prediction data.frame. Predictions are on the log scale.

Plot back-transformed model predictions of CO2 uptake by concentration for each plant different intercepts but same shape for all plants functional responses among plants are similar, but model doesnt capture all the patterns e.g.it underestimates for plant Qc2 fit another model adding on individual-plant-level smoothers allows shape of the uptake vs.concentration curve to vary between plants (but same wiggliness)
